ITEMNO_text = image_to_string(ITEMNO_cropped_image)

GOODS_cropped_image = image.crop((700, 1850, 2200, 3300))

    if len(str(x))== 0:

# Automate the cropping part
# Open PNG with cv2 module

img = cv2.imread('BLTEST.png', 0) # 0 means load the image in grayscale mode.
# set our global threshold value. 100 worked fine for me but in the documentation they suggest 127. 
# 255 is the max pixel value and last but not least I set 0 to as a style of thresholding
ret, thresh = cv2.threshold(img, 100, 255, 0) 

# A contour is a curve joining all continious points. cv2.findContours takes 3 arguments.
# First one is source image.
# Second is contour retrieval mode.
# Third is contour approximation method. And it outputs the contours and hierarchy. contours is a Python list of all the contours in the image. Each individual contour is a Numpy array of (x,y) coordinates of boundary points of the object.
image, contours, hierarchy = cv2.findContours(thresh,cv2.RETR_TREE,cv2.CHAIN_APPROX_SIMPLE) # find black lines 

# So now we pick out the largest contours with a simple for loop. 
# The borders we want are clearly the largest lines in the PNG so it should be easy to set a limit. 400 was good
# Make a copy / grab the bounds / draw over the border lines / crop / save in given directory.  
for num, large_countour_lines in enumerate(contours):
    if len(large_countour_lines) > 400:
        img_copy = img.copy()
        cnt= contours[num]
        x,y,w,h = cv2.boundingRect(cnt)
        cv2.drawContours(img_copy, [cnt], -1, color = (255, 255, 255), thickness = 10)
        crop = img_copy[y:y+h,x:x+w]
        cv2.imwrite(r'C:\Users\Dani K\auto_crop\BLTEST_crop_{}.png'.format(num),crop)
        print('Succesfully saved BLTEST_crop_{}.png'.format(num))
        
# Finally apply image_to_text() on your cropped files.
